{"/service/ndnp/idhi/batch_idhi_jerusalem_ver01/data/sn89055082/00414211148/1914020501/0046.xml":{"full_text":"THE NEZPERCE HERALD\nTHURSDAY, FEB. 5. 1914\nw. p. r.\u201eu\u00ab*r m r. w. xuea\u00bbu\nSdlton and Own\u00ab\u00ab\nHow Hug Cholera is Being Combatted.\nWashington, D. C., Jan. 31\u2014 The\nDepartment of agriculture, during\nthe past year, has been conducting a\ncampaign in Indiana, Missouri, Iowa\nand Nebraska to control the contag\nious disease of bogs known as ''hog\ncholera\" by means of anti-hog chol\nera serum and farm quarantines. In\none county (Pettis county Missouri)\nwhere there was a loss of 18 per cent\nIn 1911 and 35.6 per cent in 1913 of\nall hogs raised, there was only a loss\nof 14.7 per cent up to November\n1913. This decrease was due to the\nuse of serum, which, although not\nused there by the Department's\nagents until August. 1913, material\nly reduced the loss. About 60,000\nhogs were raised during the past\nyear and of the 10,000 that died of\nthe hog cholera only about 1,000\nwere lost after the active use of ser\num and quarantine measures were\ninaugurated.\nIn every country where these meas\nures were employed, even though be\ngun after the disease had continued\nits ravages for some time, there was\nle\u00bb lost from hog cholera than cith\ner of the two preceding years.\nIn addition to its great function as\na preventive, it has been found that\nthe anti-faog-cholera serum would\ncure a large proportion of hogs in\nthe early stages of the disease and\nrender them immune after recovery.\nHowever, if hogs are not treated by\nthis serum, from 75 to 100 per cent\nof all affected herds, die. This ser\num, so far as is known, is the only\n\u00bbhin\u00bb m,, ...__\nthing tnat wi.. prevent the disease.\nOf hogs actually sick when treat\n-j \u00bbh\u00bb\ned, the Department s msp-ctors lost j\nbut 25 per cent during the past sum- 1\nOf well hog. in diseased\nherds, 2 8 per cent died after being\ntreated and of hogs in exposed herds\nle\u00bb than 1 per cent died after being\nmer.\ninoculated with the serum.\nIn an\ninfected herd there is always a cer\ntain proportion of bogs that are\nwell.\nSome States are engaged in the\nmanufacture of serum to cure this\ndisease. This \u00bbrum requires spec\nial treatment to pre\u00bbrve its quality\nand a qualified man to produce it.\nSufficient serum to treat an average\nhundred-pound hog costs about thirty\ncents at a liberal estimate. The\ntreatment is by hypodermic injec\ntion.\nThe object of the Department has\nbeen to endeavor to control the dis\nease and if possible, to eliminate it\nfrom the country. To \u00bbcure this\nend the best efforts of the farmer\nhimself are necessary. The cam\npaign against this devasting sickness\nduring 1913 was planned in the ter\nritory \u00bblected along three lines.\nHog cholera is cao\u00bbd by a germ\nthat exists in the blood. It is an or\nganism apparently so small that the\nmost powerful microscopes do not\nshow it. However, it is easy to de\nmonstrate its presence by inoculating\na small part of the blood from a sick\nhog into a well one, which produces\nthe hog cholera.\nHog cholera is a disease which\nseems to be stopped to a degree by\nby the frosts of winter, although\nfrost cannot be said to stop a ca\u00bb\nafter it has taken hold of its victims.\nU. S. Department of Agriculture.\n.4^\n\\$i\n9*\nf\u00a3\n\n\n\nr\nJ\n9\n\u00dcK N- B MILLE! I\u00dc\ne i re I 1\n\nThe Cokabt Rato.\nThe O -W. R. N. announces\nthat from March IS to April 15, the\nfollowing one-way colonist tickets to\nPacific northwest points and to inter\nmediate points affected thereby will\napply\nMissouri river points...\nSt Paul.\nDuluth, Minn_\nChicago_ _ _\nSt. Louis, Mo._\nPeoria, HI._\nBeaumont, Tex._\nMemphis. Tenn._\nProportionate rates apply from\nother points\nWe will loan you money at 8 per\ncent on improved lands. Our connec\ntions with large mortgage, loan and\nlife insurance companies enables us\nto make exceptionally favorable rates\nto our clients. Fire insurance agent\nfor approved companies. Union\nState Bank, Nezperce. Idaho. 31tf\niaterraatwa Wanted.\nInformation wanted of the where,\nabouts of one Patrick Peters, who\nwas last beard from in Idaho.\n$30.00\n30.00\n30.00\n38 00\n37.00\n37.00\n46.05\n43.50\nHe had relatives in Nevada county,\nCalifornia.\nHe is a legatee of a\ngenerous bequest under the terms of\na will now in probate in California.\nIf he is dead, we would like to hear\nfrom his children, if he left any.\nWill you kindly give this inquiry\npublicity in your local papers \"or\notherwise?\nAlty's at Law, Nevada City, Calif\nDanger* of a Cold.\nDo you know that of all the minor ail.\neolil* are by far the moat dangerousT\nIt is not the colda themselves that you need\nto fear, b^t the serious diseases tb* thay so\noften es< j p or tfa\u00abs reason every cold\nshould be gotten rid of with the tea* poe\n\nhelp to you. It loosens a cold,\nFor sate by\nall dealer\u00bb.\u2014Advertisement. _\nThe undersigned will be thankful\nfor any information on the subject.\nVery respectfully,\nNilon Arbogast,\nFer Sale or Trade.\nDo you want a ranch? Here's a\nsnap\u2014the Wannamaker place, near\nGreer. See A. G. Gross.\nreiie?\u00abi th*\nThat Vollmer has an embryo hu\nmorist. It is a terrible thing to have,\nbut insomuch as the young man him\nself is continually perpetrating his\n\"jokes,\" the secret is bound to slip\nout sometime.\nFor a person who makes jokes this\nyoung man takes himself very sert\nously\u2014sends his stuff to the papers,\nmagazines and all that. And be\ncause of this, also his friends are\ninclined to make merry at bis ex\npense.\nA few nighls ago the friends were\nkidding him rather too vigorously\nfor his comfort.\n\"That's alt right?\" he declared\nvehemently, in reply to some partic\nularly keen thrust, \"psople laughed\nat Mark Twain when be first started\nout.\"\n\"Sure they did, you poor piece of\ncheese,\" replied the tormentor.\n\"They laughed at him until be died\n\u2014they're still laughing at him\u2014but\nnot quit: in the same way.\"\nExcellent for Stomach Trouble.\n\"Chamberlain's Tablet, are just fine for\nstomacb trouble,\" writes Mrs. O. C Dunn,\nArnold. Pa. \"I was bothered with this com\nplaint tor acme time and frequently bad bil\nious attacha Chamberlain's Tablet, afforded\nme grast relief from tbs lint, and since tak\ning one bottle of them I feel like a different\npereoo.\" For sate by all dealers.\u2014Adver\nPlenty of the long green to loan\non real estate. Low rate liberal\nterms. Tell me your wants.\nA. G. Gross, the loan man\nTHE LIVE STOCK MARKET\nReport from the Union Stock Yards\nCo., North Portland, Oregon, for\nthe week ending Jan. 31\nReceipts for the week were cat\ntle 784 calves IS sheep 6543\nhogs 5243.\nCattle liquidation has been ex\ntremely light this week and business\nnot very brisk. Packers are show\ning a preference for prime hay and\ngrain-fed steers weighing from 1050\nto 1300 pounds. Of courre this va\nriety is comparitively scarce and\nmost of the transaction are in med\nBeef out\nturn and heavy bullocks,\nlet is narrow. Decreased receipts\nhave undoubtedly had a sobering\neffect on prices, but trade is not ac\nA few good butcher\nlive as yet.\ncattle were sold during the week,\nbut the market was slow. Bulk prices\nwere as follows: prime steers, $7.35\nto $7.60 prime cows, $6 35 to $6.60\nheifers, $6 50 to $6 75; calves,\n$8.00 to 19.00; bulls, $5 50 and\n$5.75.\nSwine prices climbed to $8 15\nThursday as receipts have been very\nsmall since Monday, when the sec\nond largest run of the year arrived.\nBuying was brisk all week and\nprices maintained a strong front.\nBulk of choice light bogs brought\n$8.00 to $8 05, but occasionally sales\nwere made at $8 10 and $8. IS. De\nmand seem* to be brisk and to date\nhas taken care of the supply.\nThe sheep house experienced a\ntemporary slump this week, as killers\ndrew off unexpsctedly, and mutton\nand lamb seller* bad considerable\ndifficulty in disposing of their stock,\nespecially if quality of sheep and\niambs graded le\u00bb than prime.\nWethers were unsteady and about\nIS cents lower. Ewes fell a quarter\nand lambs an equal amount the early\npart of the week. A few top sales\nwere made Monday at the same level\nwhich ruled here tea dajrs since, but\nbusine\u00bb was draggy thereafter.\nBulk prices cm Friday were prime\nyearlings, $5 60 to $5.85 prime\newes $4.50 to $4 75. Poor quality\nmutton hard to move at any price.\nSee* Good Time*,\nAn indication of the rapidj return\nof prosperity and public confidence\ncam: last Friday in the announce\nment of officials of the Unicn Pacific\nrailroad system that this line has\nj'*t let the contracts for the building\nof 5,000 freight cars at a cost of be\ntween $5,500,000and $6,000,000 for\ndelivery beginning the middle of\nApril and as rapidly thereafter as\nthe builders can turn them out.\nNot only does this imttense order\nbear on the return of general pros\nperity, but it will mean much to the\nlumberman of the Pacific Northwes*,\nsince the greater number of these\ncars will be of wool, and the lumber\nmanufacturers of that section will of\nnecessity be called upon to supply\nmost of the lumber.\nThe Union Pacific system, which\nincludes also the Oregon-Washing\nton Railroad Navigation Company\nand the Oregon Short Line, is the\nfirst of the big railroad systems to\nexpress its confidence as to the future\nconditions of th: country.\nBiliousness and Constipation Coved.\nIf you are ever troubled with bilioness\u00ab,\nor constipation you will bs int\u00ab restai in tbs\nstatement of R. F. Erwin, Psro, lad. \"A\nyear ago la* winter I had so \u00bbUsch of indi\ngestion followed by biliousness ,n<j constipa\ntion. Seeing Chamberlain', Tablets so highly\nrecommended, 1 bought s bottle of them sod\nright away.\"\nthey helped me\nall dealers.\u2014 Advert\u00e2ga e gL\nSheriff P*ige paid the Foreste ac\ntion a business visit last Saturday.\nFor 